clue: This shiny sculpture walks the corner proudly.

title: Bull

title: Steam

title: Dialogue
clue: Look for people talking outside the city's main post office.

title: Speakers Corner
clue: Look for a women's rights advocate, Supreme Court Justice, and renowned author standing together.

title: Lion

clue: These cats guard the entrance to one of Brisbane's most iconic buildings.

title: Reverie 1

title: The Overseer
clue: You'll have to look carefully for this supervisor sitting on a ledge.

title: The Banker
clue: This large artwork celebrates the role of the money lender.

title: Petrie Tableau
clue: This sculpture, located in a major Brisbane square, commemorates the area's early settler families.

title: Navy Memorial
clue: Look near the dry warship to find this waving character.

title: Confucius
clue: This statue, located in one of Brisbane's signature park lands, was a gift for Queensland's 150th birthday.

title: Plant Form
clue: This metallic, black, stylised plant has been in Brisbane since 1988. You will find it right next to the river.

title: Cannon
clue: serial 63914

title: Jemmy Morrill and the Brolgas
clue: This statue celebrates an early European man living with Indigenous Australians.

title: Flower By the Gate
clue: This flower is also know as the Hong Kong Orchid Tree.

title: Nursing Service
clue: This memorial is one of many in the same area commemorating our military personnel. But this one is about caring, not fighting.

title: Nepalese Pagoda Peace Bell
clue: This item is a part of one of World Expo '88's most popular attractions. You may be tempted to ring it.

title: Confluence
clue: This artwork represents the judicial experience, and is located accordingly.

title: Eyes are Singing Out
clue: Normally we sing from our mouths, but not in this artwork by a well-known Japanese artist.

title: Child Abuse Memorial
clue: This memorial, located near Roma Street, reminds us that we have not always lived up to our collective responsibility for the children of the state.

title: The Human Factor Bruce the Unicyclist
clue: Balancing up high is quite a feat for this World Expo '88 character.

title: Memories of the Wind
clue: Another World Expo '88 sculpture, this one by a Japanese artist. You'll find it tucked away in one of the city's out-of-the-way parks.

title: Forms of Myth Sculpture (Agamemnon) - pyramid
clue: This sculpture, another from World Expo '88, has four parts. And for a sculpture, it's proven quite mobile, having moved twice from it's original location.

title: Approaching Equilibrium
clue: This large, abstract sculpture, industrial and insect in appearance, overlooks the river and one of Brisbane's major galleries.

title: Dinosaur
clue: This Tyrannosaurus rex is sheltered at one of Brisbane's places of learning and discovery.

title: Still Life with Landscape
clue: This artwork combines two popular painting genres, and then recreates them in steel.

title: Paradigm
clue: This artwork is but a model of the original, a World Expo '88 piece that stretched 30 metres into the sky.

title: Poinsettia Riverfire
clue: This tall sculpture, located in Emma Miller Place, combines two Brisbane cultural icons.

title: Illumicube
clue: Stay after dark and you might see this artwork light up.

title: Egle Queen of Serpents
clue: This bronze statue doesn't look like a snake, but perhaps it is related to them.

title: The World Peace Flame Monument
clue: The moths in the garden are drawn towards the flame.

title: Lobby Sculpture
clue: Look for this endless spiral near the entrance to a hotel.

title: The World Turns
clue: This artwork features two animals, one huge and the other tiny. There's also a nearby chair for contemplation.

title: Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi
clue: This famous figure was committed to non-violent protest.

title: Wind Sculpture
clue: This kinetic sculpture celebrates a boulevard that never fulfilled it's promise.

title: Resilience
clue: It would take resilience to withstand being crushed like this.

title: The Other Side of Midnight
clue: This work celebrates the special time and place that can take us away from everyday reality.

title: Casuarina Pods
clue: Look for these large spiky seed pods in the grass.

title: Canberra Times Fountain
clue: Water is only one part of this stainless steel sculpture.

title: Ainslie's Sheep
clue: Ready for shearing?

title: Life Cycle
clue: This organic shape is a metaphor for a life full of experience.

title: Icarus
clue: Don't fly too close to the sun.

title: Choice of Passage
clue: It's hard to tell, but this archway might be considered a passage.

title: ACT Memorial
clue: This sculptured memorial celebrates the people who have served the ACT.

title: Bush Pack
clue: This sculpture is by a ranger turned artist, and is connected with a documentary film.

title: The Glebe
artist: Hew Chee Fong and L M Noonan
clue: This sculpture is shaped in memory of the house that once stood here, and for which the park is named.

title: Eternity
clue: This artwork represents the artist's faith in the future of humanity.

title: Reclamation: Culture, Spirit and Place
clue: This artwork celebrates a group of people as they move forward into the future.

title: Cushion & Wedge
clue: Apparently people like to lounge on this popular artwork.

title: The Big Little Man
clue: This little man isn't so little after all.

title: Poet's Corner
clue: This may be an appropriate place to recite poetry.

title: Ethos
clue: This is one of the older public artworks around Canberra and represents the community, it's title meaning, 'the place of the living'.

title: Encasement
clue: This artwork encases a glass gallery.

title: Rabindranath Tagore
clue: This artwork depicts the first non-European Nobel Laureate.

title: Father and Son
clue: This artwork was created in memory of a well-known politician's father.

title: Al Grassby
clue: This artwork depicts a former Minister for Immigration.

title: Fractal Weave
clue: This artwork looks like a mesh or net.

title: Lola Black Lola Pink
clue: This sculpture is named after tulips.

title: Thespis
clue: A work to commemorate the originator of Greek tragedy.

title: Dream Lens for the Future
clue: Dream of the future.

title: Longitude
clue: This artwork represents separation between service personnel and their families.

title: Red and Blue
clue: This artwork creates a sense of tension and quiet strength.

title: Sky Shard Above the In Between
clue: This artwork is one of two pieces on two sides of an intersection.

title: Dreaming
clue: This long-limbed character sits, perhaps in contemplation.

title: Folding Ground Across the In Between
clue: This steel sculpture is one of a pair, and represents architectural forms and natural forms.

title: Two to Tango
clue: This is not a dance for solo performers.

title: Patria es Humanidad
clue: This Cuban sculpture symbolises connections and solidarity.

title: The Encounter
clue: This artwork was created from discarded pieces from a hydro-electricity project.

title: Vessel of (Horti)cultural Plenty
clue: This artwork, made mostly of steel and LEDs, represents flowers.

title: Here and Now
clue: This steel artwork is made of two groups of eight figures.

title: Untitled
clue: This sculpture was created by a former French rugby captain.

title: Chalchiuhtlicue
clue: This artwork was inspired by an ancient original from Mexico.

title: Fenix 2
clue: This piece commemorates a harrowing underground rescue.

title: Rapture
clue: On this corner in the CBD, two bodies meet in an unexpected way.

title: Echoes from the North
clue: You'll find this colourful three-piece sculpture near one end of Brisbane's main pedestrian malls.

title: Shrine of Remembrance
clue: The flame is never extinguished at this major landmark and ceremonial site.

title: I Love My Sunburnt Country
clue: This picture, which depicts the diversity of the Australian landscape, was exhibited as part of Maiwar.

title: The Guardian
clue: You won't find any other sculpture in Brisbane featuring a tree in a backpack, but that's exactly what this character is holding as he stands at an intersection.

title: Mooney Memorial Fountain
clue: This heritage-listed memorial, named after a volunteer fireman, has occupied its wedge-shaped lot for over 100 years.

title: El Emigrante
clue: In a park near a cathedral you'll find this memorial to Australia's Lebanese settlers.

title: Spinning Top
clue: Perhaps the cathedral was never built, but this dome reminds us that it was once slated for Brisbane.

title: Robert Burns
clue: Located in Centenary Place, this monument is dedicated to Scotland's Immortal Bard.

title: Morning Star II
clue: This shiny sculpture was originally installed in the World Expo '88 Times Square, and has subsequently been moved several times.

title: Sundial
clue: This sculpture was placed in 1999 to commemorate the 75th birthday of the park in which it's located.

title: Thomas Joseph Byrnes
clue: This statue, located in a place that might as well be called Burns Park, is a memorial to the service of one its early Parliamentarians.

title: Gifts
clue: This sculpture, located outside a well-known hotel, features two children and several birds.

title: Knots
clue: You may encounter these sculptures as you walk near the river. However, you'll never untie this bowline.

title: The Passenger
clue: This Cezary Stulgis sculpture is taking the train home.

title: Chain
clue: These three chain links are easy to overlook as you walk along Wharf Street.

title: Everyday Devotional
clue: This formless sculpture isn't located in the Botanic Gardens, but it's close by.

title: Aurora
clue: You'll find this winged sculpture near the corner of Wharf and Queen Streets.

title: Lady Diamantina Bowen
clue: This statue, located near a library, represents the wife of Queensland's first governor.

title: Perkins Stables
clue: This artwork, one of many in Brisbane by this sculptor, is a departure from his other works. It depicts a scene from a photograph of a local business.

title: HMAS Moreton Memorial
clue: This memorial marks the location of the original HMAS Moreton, and is dedicated to the W.R.A.N.S.

title: AIF World War II Memorial
clue: This memorial, located at South Bank, used to be a fountain.

title: Man and Matter
theme: Leisure in the Age of Technology
clue: You'll find these remnants of World Expo '88 scattered along the river, representing 'leisure in the age of technology'. The one you want features five people engaged in different activities, side-by-side.

title: Geerbaughs Midden
clue: This sculpture, located under some cliffs, was inspired by conversations with an elderly Indigenous man.

title: Crossover Guardians
clue: These rowboats are positioned high above the stairs, overlooking the river.

title: Preservation
clue: Look closely, and you'll see these leaf-less trees are actually covered in leaves.

title: Venus Rising
clue: This tall structure, rising over the Kangaroo Point cliffs, might just have the best views over the river, Story Bridge, and Brisbane city.

title: Sunflower Mobile
clue: Look up from this spinning artwork and you might spot St Vincent's Hospital.

title: Wormholes
clue: These colourful structures are part artwork, part playground.

title: Reflections at Midday
clue: Watch where you are walking, or you might miss this star-inspired artwork.

title: Fish Fossil
clue: This artwork, by a sculptor with many other works around the city, might as well be embedded in the cliffs that inspired it.

title: Canon Garland Memorial
clue: This memorial commemorates the founding of a very important day in the Australian calendar.

title: Flickering Wind Generator
clue: You'll have to step out over the river to find this sculpture celebrating renewable energy from before the notion was trendy.

title: Biomechanical Pelicans
clue: You won't get close to these birds, but even if you could, they wouldn't fly away.

title: Tropical Still Life
clue: This colourful mural adorns one of the city's cycle pathways. But unless you ride the bus from the centre of the city, you might have missed it.

title: Mural - Burnett Lane
clue: Search one of Brisbane's laneways, and find this reminder of the racial tensions and difficulties that still exist in this country.

title: Witnessing to Silence
clue: This sculpture, outside one of Brisbane's court buildings, has two disparate parts, and two different stories. You should take the time to read the plaque.

title: Mosaic Mural
clue: This mosaic is the public face of a building constructed to celebrate Queensland's centenary.

title: Queen Victoria
clue: One of several statues of monarchs in Brisbane, this statue presides over her own gardens, and maintains an unbroken view of the casino.

title: Royal Australia Air Force Memorial
clue: Reigned over by a queen and a former Queensland premiere, this eagle honours our service men and women.

title: Bishop James O'Quinn
clue: This statue captures the visage of Brisbane's first bishop.

title: Platypus Chair
clue: A nice place to rest and admire the monotreme.

title: Enlightenment
clue: Reach for the sun.

title: River of Stone
clue: Not all rivers flow.

title: Strength, Plenty, Production and Growth
theme: A sure friend in uncertain times
clue: You'll need to look up to see this sculpted work celebrating strength, plenty, and growth.

title: Resilience
clue: This work commemorates a struggle for equality.

title: King George V Memorial
artist: E.F. Kohler, R. Summerhayes and E.S. Taylor
clue: This royal equestrian stands in his own square.

title: Mirage
clue: Notoriously difficult to photograph.

title: Sir William Glasgow Memorial
clue: He served with Light Horse regiments, before eventually serving in the Australian Parliament and as a High Commissioner.

title: Juxtaposition 1
clue: This painted sculpture, which is part of the Expo '88 collection, was created by a South Australian artist.

title: The Rock
clue: View this artwork under the Story Bridge to see a snapshot of the political issues of 1988.

title: Vision
clue: This sculpture was made from marble from a disused mine near Cairns.

title: The Dancers
clue: This World Expo '88 era sculpture of people dancing has not always resided in its current location.

title: Night Companion (Sky Needle)
clue: This is probably the most visible art work from the World Expo '88.

title: Continuous Division
clue: This large interlocking steel sculpture seems to defy gravity. You won't find it unless you explore every corner of this large parkland.

title: Seven Versions of the Sun
clue: These seven arbours create interesting shadows as the day passes.

title: The Green Room
clue: Watch the city lights come alive at night from this high place. You may not even know it's an artwork, so look for the plaque.

title: Afforest
clue: Trees can be shaped and manipulated, as evidenced by this work.

title: Infinity Forest
clue: This printed artwork depicts a towering forest.

title: Husk (Falling from Above)
clue: You'll need to look up to see this aluminum sculpture. It's not alone, and makes up a three-piece work.

title: Once Again
clue: You'll encounter this repetitious, colourful artwork while walking through a pedestrian link.

title: Across the Ocean Their Frangrances Intermingled...
clue: Look for the colourful light falling on the ground in this laneway, and then look for where it comes from.

title: Returning (Falling from Above)
clue: One of a series of three artworks, this one represents the last stage in the life cycle.

title: Charlie Cox
clue: Pay attention, or you'll overlook this colourful artwork hidden in plain view.

title: Waterography – writing in light with water
clue: A pool's surface reflected on an atrium's windows.

title: Efflorescence – architectural epiphyte #9
clue: These organic forms add a flourish to a Mary Street building.

title: Gravity Circle
clue: These geometric shapes give the feeling of balanced energy.

title: Grow
clue: This flat metal sculpture looks like it might have been inspired by a plant, or perhaps fire.

title: Seqvanae
clue: This artwork represents health and medicine, which is appropriate given its location.

title: Sculpture No 23 (The Parcel)
clue: This is a package that looks like it may have been handled poorly.

title: Untitled
clue: You'll need to look up to see this unconventional artwork.

title: Circuitry
clue: This artwork represents a grid, and the connections between our bodies and our cities.

title: Ebb and Flow
clue: These sculptures reflect the busy street to capture the movement and colour.

title: Twilight
clue: This artwork is part part sculpture, part landscape, and part architectural design.

title: On The Staircase
clue: "The more I read, the smaller I feel."

title: Chit Chat
clue: It's hard to find information about this sculpture, but these two abstract figures might just be talking.

title: Torri
clue: This artwork symbolises a gate between the spiritual and physical worlds.

title: Shades of Green
clue: You could easily walk under this artwork without even knowing it's there. Look for colours, including green.

title: The Witness Box
clue: This artwork, which looks like falling books or boxes, is part of Griffith University's Art Collection.

title: Leviathan Play
clue: You might pass this twisted sculpture when visiting the museum.

title: Pelicans
clue: These birds, created by well-known sculptors Leonard and Kathleen Shillam, are never far from the water, though they always remain in the view of Brisbane's art lovers.

title: Offshoot
clue: If you cross the Victoria Bridge, you'll have a 50/50 chance of seeing this large sculpture that's both industrial-scale, and organically-inspired.

title: Gates of Heaven
clue: You'll need to explore the small park at the north-western edge of the CBD to find this gate.

title: Confluenza
clue: It's not often you find a solid marble outdoor set. But if you explore one of the city's largest parks, you might come across this artwork.

title: SPQR
clue: Look at the cars sitting in a large rail depot, and you might recognise the inspiration for this artwork.

title: Emblem
clue: This giant redhead looks like it's rushing to get to the train station.

title: Frogs Hollow
clue: You'll have to look carefully around every corner to find this artwork of found objects, with the same pedigree as kangaroos, pelicans, and a certain fish skeleton.

title: If Only You Knew
clue: You've probably never seen this mural. But if you take some stairs towards the Story Bridge, you might just find it.

title: Freshwater Lens
clue: What to do with the space under a major city arterial road? Fill it with an artwork that celebrates more natural environments.

title: Mates
clue: These best friends love hanging out in the South Bank gardens. You'll find them near one of it's playgrounds.

title: One For All
clue: A suitcase and photos from around the world.

title: Pamphlet
clue: Go to the place where Brisbane puts on some of it's biggest meetings and shows, and you might find this colourful set of geometric shapes.

title: Time and Tide
clue: They look like steps leading from a lawn next to the river. But look closer, and you'll see a story.

title: Coolaman
clue: This shiny sculpture doubles as a water playground attraction.

title: Pir'ri
clue: You'll find this artwork, made of several shiny pieces, near the place where many other aspiring artists learn their trade.

title: Divided
clue: You've probably passed this very large artwork a thousand times and never known it's there. Remember, buildings can contain artworks too.

title: UFO
clue: Did this West End sculpture come from another planet?

title: The Tidal Indicator
clue: You'll find this archway as the gateway to one of Brisbane's river walkways.

title: Automatic For The People (ROCK)
clue: The name of this art work is similar to a popular REM album.

title: Equilibrium
clue: This imposing artwork, created by a Japanese Artist, represents a sword and scale. It's located where you would expect to find metaphorical scales.

title: Christ Accepting His Cross
clue: This statue represents a cornerstone of the Christian faith.

title: Alethea Beetson
clue: This portrait, found in the CBD, celebrates working with Indigenous Australian youths.

title: Blood
clue: Two sculptures stand side by side. This one represents Jesus Christ's blood.

title: unknown
clue: You will have search for this mural, well known by cyclists, but out of the view of most people.

title: Sleeping Languages in Queensland
clue: You will find this mural in the city's main university campus, next to where small children play.

title: Water
clue: Two sculptures stand side by side. This one represents water.

title: Collective
clue: Step back from these boxes, and they can take on the appearance of characters in another language.

title: Cicada
clue: Wait for a bus on the south side of the river, and you'll see this giant insect.

title: A Life Long Promise
clue: This art work, at Legacy House, pays tribute to those who have served.

title: Gravity with Gravitas and Bars
clue: Look for a laneway sculpture inspired by paper aeroplanes and flying service medals.

title: Echo
clue: These colourful acrylic discs can be found hanging in a popular Brisbane laneway.

title: Rise
clue: These busts, located in a place of learning, show the casting process.

title: Scattered Thoughts
clue: Look at the ground to see these scattered leaves on a walkway in the CBD.

title: Greener Dogman and Rabbitwoman
clue: These two South Brisbane animals wouldn't normally get along, but through love, they now keep each other company forever.

title: Landlines
clue: Remember to look up and all around to find this large art work depicting a topographical map of Brisbane's environs.

title: Queensland Police Memorial
clue: In its relocation from George Street, this important memorial was much enhanced, and now features prominently in its green surrounds.

title: Head in the Clouds 2
clue: This six-story mural celebrating Brisbane's lost textile factories is hard to miss.

title: Steam Machine
clue: Two abstract artworks sit on a South Brisbane corner. If you look closely, you will see they are jets of steam, perpetually frozen.

title: The Finished Wall
clue: In a lane filled with murals, it could be easy to overlook another. But not this one, created by an artist who has joked that his name sounds like it comes from a Hallmark card.

title: Steam Fish
clue: Another sculpture sitting on a corner, this time on a lane named after a man, not an animal.

title: The Harvest
clue: If you like wine, you'll love this enormous mural celebrating the process of wine-making.

title: Tide
clue: You can see your reflection in this sculpture located on Ann Street.

title: The Iconoclast's Last Word
clue: This artwork looks like something you might find in a child's pencil case.

title: The Elements
clue: One element is used to make four.

title: The Connection
clue: It's easy to miss this silhouette against a Queensland sunset if you are walking the wrong direction on Mary Street.

title: Water Blocks
artist: Hew Chee Fong and L.M. Noonan
clue: These stones, located in one of the gateways to an important city park, look like they are collecting pools of water.

title: We are Shipwrecked and Landlocked
clue: You'll need to take a look out the back of one of Queensland's premier galleries to find these 'trees'.

title: Tow Row
clue: This artwork, cast from a real object, commemorates a people's connection to and reliance on the river.

title: Music Walk
clue: Most people walk past these embellishments without knowing they are there. Look for the colourful pieces on the wall of the place where people learn to play music.

title: Nice to Meet You Again
clue: You'll find this artwork above the South Brisbane shop known for selling coffee and cigars.

title: Grateful Fateful Sunshine Rain
clue: Look up for this artwork to see it respond to real-time weather data.

title: The Carpet of Echidna
clue: You won't find this snake-inspired artwork on the footpath, but will need to search a riverside breezeway instead.

title: Dr Clem Jones AO
clue: This statue celebrates the longest serving mayor of Brisbane. It's located outside a building he must have known well.

title: Progress of civilisation in the state of Queensland or Tympanum of the Pediment
clue: Raise your eyes to see this depiction of explorers, industrialists, and artists spreading across the land.

title: Sisters
clue: These two women spend their time sitting outside a major Brisbane cultural landmark.

title: Flow
clue: These metallic sculptures can be found hanging out near the seat of QLD's governmental and political power.

title: Bowers
clue: These three arches are inspired by nature, and stand not far from the Botanic Gardens.

title: The Postcard Project
clue: This South Brisbane project incorporates responses from the community about the area in which they live.

title: Q150 Time Capsule
clue: Queensland's memories have been buried here, but they will be recovered when the time comes.

title: Edison Lane Pavement
clue: This artwork is very unconventional, and is probably overlooked by most of the people who tread over it every day.

title: CODE - Efflorescence
clue: These bubbly sculptures are definitely out of reach, here in was once Soda Water Lane?

title: The High / Perpetual Xmas, No Abstractions
clue: This artwork looks like it has sprung from a 1950's American highway, or perhaps Las Vegas. It's visible from a distance, but you'll have to travel quite a distance to reach it.

title: unknown
clue: This black and white, energetic mural contains a horse, pineapple, sword, and all manner of things.

title: Gold Ripples
clue: This fish bowl, located under the train tracks, is larger than most.

title: Rival Channels
clue: You will need to venture off the street to find this artwork, a large wall of text. And look at the plaque for the theme, but be sure to read the text.

title: Totems of Nature
clue: You'll find this mural by a Colombian street artist in a very colourful lane.

title: Quadrants, Bloom Series
clue: You will find this wall decoration in a passageway off Mary Street.

title: Horse
clue: This horse, or perhaps horses, hang out under the railway tracks surrounded by peers.

title: Muhammed Ali
clue: Hello Please, it's the boxer anyone in the world would recognise.

title: Fish Lane
clue: It's by far the longest artwork in the Art Hunt, and to say it's in one place might be misleading. Follow it, and you'll be introduced to many other artworks.

title: West of the Sea
clue: This is one part of a two-part mural, but we're giving double points due to the height, size, and separation of these artworks. This part hark backs to the namesake of the lane on which it can be found.

title: Pocket Park
clue: This is a subtle, understanded, and unconventional artwork. In fact, there's a good chance you'll miss it completely if you don't pay attention. But don't worry, there are some major works nearby, including an iconic neighbour.

title: East of the Mountains
clue: This is one part of a very large two-part mural. Together, they describe Brisbane's location in relation to major geographic features. This one does not refer to the ocean.

title: Queensland Great Awards
clue: This is neither an artwork, nor a memorial. But it's still an important landmark. Here you'll find the names announced each year on 6 June.

title: Topiary Suprise
clue: This collection of sculptures is by a sculptor whose works can be found scattered around the city. They are inspired to look like trees that are sculpted to look like something else. The name of their location, situated in one of Brisbane City's biggest gardens, offers a clue to the theme.

title: Blue Dragon
clue: This mythical creature is much smaller than it's usually depicted in fantasies and nightmares. It's hiding in the trees, bring goodwill to all who pass.

title: The Trapeze Artist
clue: This guy has been hanging around in one form or another since 1988. Although he used to call South Bank home, he can now be found at the entrance to a prominent square's carpark.

title: Humpback Whales
clue: This is not an artwork, per se, but it's still a work of art. These are perhaps the most lifelike depictions in the entire Art Hunt, and the location explains why this must be.

title: Roma Street Police Station Memorial
clue: This memorial was erected to commemorate a police station that stood on the spot from 1879 to 1968.

title: Paw Paw and Mango Trees
clue: Keep an eye on the buildings near the St Stephen Cathedral if you want to find these fruit trees.

title: The Juggler
clue: Standing below this guy, another homage to World Expo '88, could be dangerous if he was really doing what's portrayed.

title: Unison
clue: It's not clear what this suspended Ann Street sculpture represents. But it's pretty, and looks like it could be structural.

title: Afloat
clue: This mural created as, part of Pillars Project, features the name of its location.

title: Takdanai (Sang Tong)
clue: The title of this large picture on Cordelia Street translates to 'Golden Shell'.

title: Daejeon and Brisbane Friendship Stone
clue: A gift from Korea, nestled near the rainforest.

title: Themis
clue: This well-known goddess and symbol was moved when her former home was demolished. But lucky for us, and justice, she found a new place to live in 2012.

title: Australia - Japan Friendship Stone
clue: On the southern side of the river, two similarly themed works sit almost together. This is the oldest of the two.

title: A23/23
clue: This is one of two works situated together that barely see the light of day. You'll have to cross the road to read it.

title: Diapason
clue: Sadly, most people only encounter this metal artwork when parking their cars for a show or day out at the park. Good luck working out what it represents.

title: City Roos
clue: These lounging marsupials, created by an artist with many works around the city, appear in several locations.

title: Symbols of an Extraordinary Life
clue: Another unconventional and enormous artwork that stretches over a large space. Yet you might still miss it if you don't look closely.

title: Frameworks
clue: It's easy to miss this artwork leading to amenities.

title: Jennifer
clue: You will have to look inside to see this Expo performer.

title: Drift
clue: It's not clear how these giant seedpods got here, but sit down to have a coffee, and you can't miss them.

title: Freedom Bound
clue: This boat was inspired by convicts, but now mostly holds children.

title: Passing Through
clue: If you start the Art Hunt at QUT, this colourful wall is just around the corner, in a busy corridor. If you do not, you now know where to find it.

title: Net
clue: Once located on the Neville Bonner building, this sculpture was relocated to another prominent government building, though you might not have noticed it before.

title: unknown
clue: This parade of black and white animals by a Chinese artist seem to flow along the wall.

title: unknown
clue: You will find this artwork hiding utilities at the entrance to Howard Smith Wharves.

title: Freshwater - Saltwater Story
clue: You will have to travel far to find this small bronze art work, nestled in a Brisbane rainforest.

title: Untitled
clue: This mural looks like only a part of the giant, photo-like works this artist is known for. You will find his works on buildings around the world.

title: Flood Marker
clue: The years 1974 and 2011 feature prominently on this memorial.

title: Infiltration
clue: A sculpture of wood and porcelain in three parts, though you will probably only see one, sitting between escalators.

title: Walter Hill Fountain
clue: Water has stopped flowing at this historic landmark, but it is still worth a visit to learn more about this history of an important Brisbane green space.

title: unknown
clue: You will have to search carefully for this underground art work somewhere along Wharf Street, and even then you might be locked out.

title: unknown
clue: One of two murals by the same artist, for the same project. You will know this one by the flowing bright hair.

title: unknown
clue: You may never have noticed this large bird and bee friend, but travel through a certain underpass and you cannot miss it.

title: South African War Memorial
clue: This statue is one of many in this well-known square. This particular memorial may commonly be known by three different names.

title: Pink Bunny
clue: This pink creature made his first appearance during the 2013 Brisbane Festival.

title: The Glad Tomorrow
clue: The tree is a powerful symbol for growth and healing, and this sculpture celebrates that in a not-obvious way.

title: Furling
clue: This hull-inspired sculpture celebrates the transformation of Mary Street.

title: Bodhi Tree Project
clue: This artwork consists of a sacred tree and marble seats. You will find it near a great trove of art.

title: Luminous Cloud
clue: This artwork, in South Brisbane, was inspired by Brisbane's summer clouds.

title: The Colour, Community & Hope
clue: This sculpture can be found at a place that is trying to deal with homelessness.

title: Mangrove Poem
clue: This colourful mangrove bird is a relative newcomer to Brisbane.

title: Mangrove Poem
clue: It is not obvious, but you can read this art work and get a clue about the theme.

title: Floodlines
clue: Inspired by ink on water, this artwork references Brisbane's 2011 flood.

title: Flux
clue: This aluminium artwork is inspired by the tannin coloured surface of the river.

title: unknown
clue: This crocodile can be found on a substation in West End.

title: Looking Forward, Looking Back
artist: Laurie Nilsen, Gordon Hookey, Venetia Tyson, Jenny Martinelli, Lily Eather, Debbie, Sophie, Nikki Taylor
clue: You will find this mural under the William Jolly bridge, not far from a major gallery.

title: Cell
clue: This memorial, located near a rail bridge, recognises the children who were let down by the state.

title: Like the Air I Breathe (Como El Aire Que Respiro)
clue: Whether jogging or cycling, this artwork wants you to think about the air you are breathing.

title: The Birds
clue: These birds overlook the Maritime Museum.

title: unknown
clue: You will find this colourful mural in one  of the city's underpasses.

title: unknown
clue: It's not clear what this giant is reading. But even if the books had titles, he wouldn't see them.

title: Bunya Nuts
clue: This subtle artwork is easy to miss. Located in a place of gathering, it celebrates a gathering by Indigenous Australians.

title: Untitled
clue: This is a striking piece of street art in the West End, but it's not clear what it's meaning is.

title: Korea Malaya BOrneo War Memorial
clue: There are many statues here. This one commemorates Australian involvement in several Asian conflicts.

title: Women's War Memorial
clue: This piece, created by an important Brisbane sculptor, can be found almost under an eternal flame.

title: South West Pacific Campaign Memorial
clue: This World War II memorial shows a wounded soldier being helped, and a comrade facing the task ahead.

title: Vietnam War Memorial
clue: This memorial recognises the service of personnel in a long-running and generally unpopular conflict.

title: To the Memory of the Fallen
clue: This memorial commemorates all conflicts from World War I to Vietnam. You will find it in a Memorial Park.

title: Australian Vietnamese War Memorial
clue: You will need to visit the northwest corner of a large park to find a cluster of memorials, including this one commemorating a South-East Asian conflict.

title: Flood
clue: This mural was inspired by a notable event in Brisbane in 2011.

title: Untitled
clue: These strange figures are emerging from somewhere else on pillar 17.

title: Untitled
clue: The first of a number of pillars, this painting depicts a face of the future.

title: Andy Birgan
clue: This painting represents a person who has been working in the nearby milk factory for more than 30 years.

title: Untitled
clue: This railroad pillar is covered in large, colourful shapes.

title: Untitled
clue: Colour isn't needed to give this large female face impact. But the story behind the image isn't clear.

title: Other Shores
clue: This pillar, painted by two artists, uses a large blue brush stroke to represent the river between opposing shores.

title: Raise the Vibration
clue: This person is up to his neck in water and musical notes.

title: Untitled
clue: This mural features a woman surrounded by hummingbirds and hibiscus flowers.

title: Untitled
clue: This mural presents an Indigenous woman as a Mother Earth figure in purple and blue.

title: Untitled
clue: This large mural in gray-scale depicts an Indigenous youth to represent the division within Australian society. It is by an artist who has painted another large mural next to the South Brisbane railroad track.

title: Utopia
clue: At first it's easy to miss the meaning of this wall with motorcycles parked against it. But take some time to read it, and you will find a better world.

title: Ninglaana
clue: This is another Pillars Project mural, but isolated from most of the others. It celebrates the voice of Indigenous Australia.

title: Untitled
clue: This painting is hidden in an alley, and you've probably passed it many times. It celebrates cross-cultural dialogue and other ways of seeing and understanding.
